@Dr. Y
But the whole theme is DOUBLE NEGATIVES. Two YESes would be a double positive, which is not a thing. Putting YES into the squares also wouldn't have satisfied the down answers.

You are only supposed to enter two NOs, which makes an imaginary YES. Entering YES means you did the puzzle incorrectly, so it shouldn't be accepted.

@Zack

I agree, and the downs receive exactly what they need, and nothing else. The letters before the / become part of the horizontal, and the letters after the slash become part of the vertical. Completely standard convention for rebus squares, which is explained here:

<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/12/08/crosswords/rebus-crossword-puzzle.html" target="_blank">https://www.nytimes.com/2023/12/08/crosswords/rebus-crossword-puzzle.html</a>

